postTitle:
Divorce is an option. 
 
It is funny that those who oppose divorce are product of successful marriages and typical Filipino family settings.
 
Let those who are suffering from failed marriages decide what is best for them. Divorce may not be the best solution, but it is an option that gives a breath of fresh air to those living in traumatic, toxic, and life-threatening marriages. 

Walay problema if dili ta ganahan og divorce, but let's give this option to those who badly need it and give them access to affordable divorce, eapil nalang pod annulment.
text:
Maybe not everyone knows that when a priest or pastor celebrates marital rites, he uses two (2) licenses or authorities. One is from the church ( derived from a Canon Law when you are a Roman Catholic), and the other is from the civil or legal aspect (from the Civil and Family Code). The Divorce Bill will only affect the 2nd authority or legal aspect of the marriage. With regard to the 1st authority, or the Church, it will remain valid and intact based on different religious doctrines. So what will happen is that you are divorced in the civil aspect but not in the eyes of your church. In other words, why are we using faith and church doctrines when the subject of the Bill is merely the civil or legal aspect of marriage and not the religious sense? The latter remain intact and valid. 

Thanks for the nice and healthy exchange of opinions.

text:
JR AQ Legal Separation, Generally

Legal separation is a legal remedy for couples suffering from a problematic marriage. In legal separation, the couple is allowed to live apart and separately own assets. However, legally separated couples are not permitted to remarry, since their marriage is still considered valid and subsisting. Legal separation dissolves the property relations of the spouses and removes the guilty party’s capacity to inherit from the innocent party. The grounds for legal separation may have arisen after the marriage, and may be filed on the following grounds: (1)  repeated physical violence or grossly abusive conduct directed against the petitioner, a common child, or a child of the petitioner; (2)  physical violence or moral pressure to compel the petitioner to change religious or political affiliation; (3)  attempt of respondent to corrupt or induce the petitioner, a common child, or a child of the petitioner, to engage in prostitution, or connivance in such corruption or inducement; (4)  final judgment sentencing the respondent to imprisonment of more than 6 years, even if pardoned; (5)  drug addiction or habitual alcoholism of the respondent; (6)  lesbianism or homosexuality of the respondent; (7)  contracting by the respondent of a subsequent bigamous marriage, whether in the Philippines or abroad; (8)  sexual infidelity or perversion; (9)  attempt by the respondent against the life of the petitioner; or (10)  abandonment of petitioner by respondent without justifiable cause for more than 1 year.

postTitle:
Divorce is an option. 
 
It is funny that those who oppose divorce are product of successful marriages and typical Filipino family settings.
 
Let those who are suffering from failed marriages decide what is best for them. Divorce may not be the best solution, but it is an option that gives a breath of fresh air to those living in traumatic, toxic, and life-threatening marriages. 

Walay problema if dili ta ganahan og divorce, but let's give this option to those who badly need it and give them access to affordable divorce, eapil nalang pod annulment.
text:
Johanna Marie Maghinay Sumalpong ito ang katunayan maam. Basahin mo ng maigi at unawain kung ano ang pagkakaiba sa tatlo. ANNULMENT, LEGAL SEPARATION AT DIVORCE. 
1. Ano ang annulment? 

Answer. Kapag "annuled" na ang isang couple, idinedeklara na walang bisa o "void" ang kasal nila from the start. In other words, walang totoong kasal na naganap sa kanila. Kaya, pwede silang mag-asawa ulit kasi hindi naman talaga sila totoong kasal simula't sapul. Walang marriage na binubuwag sa annulment kasi walang totoong marriage na naganap. 

PS. Ang "annulment" na pinag-uusapan ko rito ay CHURCH ANNULMENT at hindi CIVIL ANNULMENT.

2. Ano ang legal separation? 

Answer. Sa legal separation magkahiwalay ang couple pero hindi pwedeng mag-asawa ulit dahil "valid" ang marriage nila. Makoconsider na "adultery" kapag nakapagrelasyon sa iba. Isang MALAKING KASALANAN ang adultery na pwedeng magdala sa atin sa impyerno. 

3. Ano ang divorce? 

Answer. Sa divorce magkahiwalay ang couple at pwedeng magpakasal ulit kahit na "valid" ang marriage nila. 

Sabi ng Panginoong Hesus, "Ang pinagsama ng Diyos ay huwag paghiwalayin ng tao (MARK 10:9)." 

Sa divorce, ginagawa na lang "temporary contract" ang marriage imbes na "lifetime commitment" ito. Nagiging CHEAP ang value ng marriage dahil mas dadami pa ang mga couple na magpapakasal kahit hindi pa handa. 

"Magpakasal na tayo. Total, pwede naman tayong magdivorce anytime kung gugustohin natin," malamang ito ang magiging usual reason sa pagpapakasal kung magiging legal ang divorce. 

4. Papano yung mga pamilyang sirang-sira na? 

Answer. Sa mga pamilyang sirang-sira na, meron namang annulment at legal separation. So, no need na ang divorce. 

Ipakulong nyo ang abusive partner. May VAWC law po tayo.

5. Diba pareho lang namang naghihiwalay ang couple sa annulment, legal separation, at divorce? 

Answer. Oo. Parehong naghihiwalay pero MAGKAIBA pa rin ang case at nature. 

Sa annulment hindi nasisira ang SANCTITY OF MARRIAGE kasi wala namang marriage na nangyari in the first place.

Sa legal separation naman, kahit na magkahiwalay ang mag-asawa, eh hindi naman pwedeng mag-asawa ulit kasi ADULTERY yun. Malaking kasalanan yun. Tsaka may chance pang magbalikan ang couple kung sakali. 

Sa divorce, sinisira nito ang SANCTITY OF MARRIAGE kasi kahit na valid ang kasal, ihinihiwalay pa rin ang couple at binibigyan sila ng karapatan na mag-asawa ulit which is ADULTERY. Divorce promotes adultery. Divorce promotes sin. Divorce promotes hell. 

In addition, mas lumalabo ang chance na ma save pa ang marriage kasi binigbiyan ng right na mag-asawa ulit sa iba. 

6. Mahal at matagal ang proseso ng annulment. Kaya, kailangan ilegalize ang divorce.

Answer. Yun pala e. Ang process pala ang problema. So, yun dapat ang i-fix. Dapat gumawa ng hakbang ang kongreso, together with the Church, para mas mapadali at maging affordable ang annulment process. So, di na kailangan pang ipush ang divorce. Kailangan lang ayusin ang annulment process sa bansa.

7. Hayaan na lang natin ang mga couple kung ano ang gusto nilang option. Wala kayong karapatan na manghimasok sa buhay nila. Tsaka, hindi naman lahat Katoliko. Hindi lahat naniniwala sa Bibliya.

Answer: Hindi natin pwedeng bigyan ng MALING OPTION ang tao. Maling option po ang divorce. Kagaya lang yan sa abortion at suicide. 

"Sanctity of Marriage" na po ang nakasalalay dito. Kaya dapat kaming mag-ingay against divorce. Kapag binibigyan natin ng karapatan ang tao na sirain ang "sanctity of marriage", binibigyan na rin natin siya ng karapatan na sirain ang pamilya. Kapag sira ang pamilya, sira rin ang lipunan.

For those who are trying to seek research-based evidences showing negative effects of divorce, please read here:

https://m.facebook.com/story.php?story_fbid=2484939021772534&id=1875469692719473

SIDLAK

#NOtoDivorce #SavetheFamily

text:
Johanna Marie Maghinay Sumalpong Legal Separation lang ang kailangan sa ganyang problema.
Legal Separation, Generally

Legal separation is a legal remedy for couples suffering from a problematic marriage. In legal separation, the couple is allowed to live apart and separately own assets. However, legally separated couples are not permitted to remarry, since their marriage is still considered valid and subsisting. Legal separation dissolves the property relations of the spouses and removes the guilty party’s capacity to inherit from the innocent party. The grounds for legal separation may have arisen after the marriage, and may be filed on the following grounds: (1)  repeated physical violence or grossly abusive conduct directed against the petitioner, a common child, or a child of the petitioner; (2)  physical violence or moral pressure to compel the petitioner to change religious or political affiliation; (3)  attempt of respondent to corrupt or induce the petitioner, a common child, or a child of the petitioner, to engage in prostitution, or connivance in such corruption or inducement; (4)  final judgment sentencing the respondent to imprisonment of more than 6 years, even if pardoned; (5)  drug addiction or habitual alcoholism of the respondent; (6)  lesbianism or homosexuality of the respondent; (7)  contracting by the respondent of a subsequent bigamous marriage, whether in the Philippines or abroad; (8)  sexual infidelity or perversion; (9)  attempt by the respondent against the life of the petitioner; or (10)  abandonment of petitioner by respondent without justifiable cause for more than 1 year.

text:
Louiee Nichan Thank you for your comment. I respect your opinion and will not argue against it. But since you throw a question at me, I'll spend a minute to answer it. 

Maybe not everyone knows that when a priest or pastor celebrates marital rites, he uses two (2) licenses or authorities. One is from the church ( derived from a Canon Law when you are a Roman Catholic), and the other is from the civil or legal aspect (from the Civil and Family Code). The Divorce Bill will only affect the 2nd authority or legal aspect of the marriage. With regard to the 1st authority, or the Church, it will remain valid and intact based on different religious doctrines. So what will happen is that you are divorced in the civil aspect but not in the eyes of your church. In other words, why are we using faith and church doctrines when the subject of the Bill is merely the civil or legal aspect of marriage and not the religious sense? The latter remain intact and valid. 

Now with that context, let's go to the the "vow and promise in COURT" as mentioned. In legal parlance, promises and vows don't usually create legal actions. The only reason why marital promises and vows in COURT have tooth and significance is because of the law in Civil and Family Code. Exactly, thats what the Bill is going to change so that legally divorce will become an option. 

Thanks for the nice and healthy exchange of opinions.

text:
I understand that once you commit to the sacrament of marriage, you become united as one. Problems, successes, and losses of both shall truly become interconnected after commitment to marriage. However, not all people living in marriage can endure every ounce of pain, harassment and violence that their partner constantly afflicts on them.

It doesn't solve abusive marriages, but it will grant a person the freedom to get out of utterly troubled married life, slowly heal from the trauma of the instance of making one question about his/her existence, and potentially break the chains of the partner's love wrapped in evilness. Let's be real; love is not present anymore if one is severely maltreated, degraded and abused.

My view may be against the teachings of the Catholic Church's scriptures resulting to making others question my identity as a Catholic Christian, but seeing fellows live a life with someone who makes them feel devalued all over again makes me advocate for their welfare and contribute to the growing call of the voices of those who favor legalizing divorce in the Philippines. 

If not now, then when? 

Pass the DIVORCE BILL now!

divorce: cheaper, less hassle because there are fewer restrictions. hence, those who REALLY NEEDS it would be able to AFFORD it.

The Bible has various teachings regarding marriage, relationships, and living a single life. Here are some key points:

1. **Marriage**: The Bible places a strong emphasis on the institution of marriage. In Genesis, marriage is described as a union created by God (Genesis 2:24). Jesus also affirmed the sanctity of marriage (Matthew 19:4-6).

2. **Singleness**: The Bible does not mandate marriage for all. The Apostle Paul, in 1 Corinthians 7, speaks positively about singleness, suggesting that it allows for greater devotion to God without the distractions of marital responsibilities (1 Corinthians 7:32-35). Paul himself was single and viewed it as a gift from God (1 Corinthians 7:7).

3. **Sexual Relations**: The Bible generally teaches that sexual relations should occur within the bounds of marriage. For example, Hebrews 13:4 states, "Marriage should be honored by all, and the marriage bed kept pure, for God will judge the adulterer and all the sexually immoral."

4. **Living Together Without Marriage**: The Bible does not explicitly address modern concepts of cohabitation without marriage, but its teachings on sexual morality imply that such arrangements are not in alignment with biblical principles.

5. **Children Outside of Marriage**: The Bible emphasizes the importance of raising children within the context of a family. However, it also provides grace and guidance for all situations, emphasizing love, responsibility, and care for children regardless of the circumstances of their birth.

In summary, while the Bible promotes marriage as the ideal context for sexual relations and raising children, it also recognizes the value of singleness and the importance of living a life devoted to God. The concept of living together and having children outside of marriage does not align with traditional biblical teachings on sexual morality and family structure.

postTitle:
Divorce is an option. 
 
It is funny that those who oppose divorce are product of successful marriages and typical Filipino family settings.
 
Let those who are suffering from failed marriages decide what is best for them. Divorce may not be the best solution, but it is an option that gives a breath of fresh air to those living in traumatic, toxic, and life-threatening marriages. 

Walay problema if dili ta ganahan og divorce, but let's give this option to those who badly need it and give them access to affordable divorce, eapil nalang pod annulment.
text:
1. Ano ang annulment? 

Answer. Kapag "annuled" na ang isang couple, idinedeklara na walang bisa o "void" ang kasal nila from the start. In other words, walang totoong kasal na naganap sa kanila. Kaya, pwede silang mag-asawa ulit kasi hindi naman talaga sila totoong kasal simula't sapul. Walang marriage na binubuwag sa annulment kasi walang totoong marriage na naganap. 

PS. Ang "annulment" na pinag-uusapan ko rito ay CHURCH ANNULMENT at hindi CIVIL ANNULMENT.

2. Ano ang legal separation? 

Answer. Sa legal separation magkahiwalay ang couple pero hindi pwedeng mag-asawa ulit dahil "valid" ang marriage nila. Makoconsider na "adultery" kapag nakapagrelasyon sa iba. Isang MALAKING KASALANAN ang adultery na pwedeng magdala sa atin sa impyerno. 

3. Ano ang divorce? 

Answer. Sa divorce magkahiwalay ang couple at pwedeng magpakasal ulit kahit na "valid" ang marriage nila. 

Sabi ng Panginoong Hesus, "Ang pinagsama ng Diyos ay huwag paghiwalayin ng tao (MARK 10:9)." 

Sa divorce, ginagawa na lang "temporary contract" ang marriage imbes na "lifetime commitment" ito. Nagiging CHEAP ang value ng marriage dahil mas dadami pa ang mga couple na magpapakasal kahit hindi pa handa. 

"Magpakasal na tayo. Total, pwede naman tayong magdivorce anytime kung gugustohin natin," malamang ito ang magiging usual reason sa pagpapakasal kung magiging legal ang divorce. 

4. Papano yung mga pamilyang sirang-sira na? 

Answer. Sa mga pamilyang sirang-sira na, meron namang annulment at legal separation. So, no need na ang divorce. 

Ipakulong nyo ang abusive partner. May VAWC law po tayo.

5. Diba pareho lang namang naghihiwalay ang couple sa annulment, legal separation, at divorce? 

Answer. Oo. Parehong naghihiwalay pero MAGKAIBA pa rin ang case at nature. 

Sa annulment hindi nasisira ang SANCTITY OF MARRIAGE kasi wala namang marriage na nangyari in the first place.

Sa legal separation naman, kahit na magkahiwalay ang mag-asawa, eh hindi naman pwedeng mag-asawa ulit kasi ADULTERY yun. Malaking kasalanan yun. Tsaka may chance pang magbalikan ang couple kung sakali. 

Sa divorce, sinisira nito ang SANCTITY OF MARRIAGE kasi kahit na valid ang kasal, ihinihiwalay pa rin ang couple at binibigyan sila ng karapatan na mag-asawa ulit which is ADULTERY. Divorce promotes adultery. Divorce promotes sin. Divorce promotes hell. 

In addition, mas lumalabo ang chance na ma save pa ang marriage kasi binigbiyan ng right na mag-asawa ulit sa iba. 

6. Mahal at matagal ang proseso ng annulment. Kaya, kailangan ilegalize ang divorce.

Answer. Yun pala e. Ang process pala ang problema. So, yun dapat ang i-fix. Dapat gumawa ng hakbang ang kongreso, together with the Church, para mas mapadali at maging affordable ang annulment process. So, di na kailangan pang ipush ang divorce. Kailangan lang ayusin ang annulment process sa bansa.

7. Hayaan na lang natin ang mga couple kung ano ang gusto nilang option. Wala kayong karapatan na manghimasok sa buhay nila. Tsaka, hindi naman lahat Katoliko. Hindi lahat naniniwala sa Bibliya.

Answer: Hindi natin pwedeng bigyan ng MALING OPTION ang tao. Maling option po ang divorce. Kagaya lang yan sa abortion at suicide. 

"Sanctity of Marriage" na po ang nakasalalay dito. Kaya dapat kaming mag-ingay against divorce. Kapag binibigyan natin ng karapatan ang tao na sirain ang "sanctity of marriage", binibigyan na rin natin siya ng karapatan na sirain ang pamilya. Kapag sira ang pamilya, sira rin ang lipunan.

For those who are trying to seek research-based evidences showing negative effects of divorce, please read here:

https://m.facebook.com/story.php?story_fbid=2484939021772534&id=1875469692719473

SIDLAK

#NOtoDivorce #SavetheFamily

text:
I have my question para sa mga tao nga agree sa Divorce. This is not to entice a debate or an argument, gusto lang ko makabalo sa inyohang own perspective and thoughts. Naa namay mga exisiting nga laws such as annulment para sa legal separation, and then VAWC para sa mga babae nga gina abuse sa ilahang partners. Are these so useless nga need ug divorce? Why can't we just strengthen these laws? Para mas dali ug affordable sya. 

Another thing nga akonh pangutana is, how confident are you na you'll find the right partner? Diba murag ma cheapen ang value sa marriage? Mura nalang sya ug uyab uyab and there's really no sense of commitment?
